@Tutorial(time: 20) {
    @Intro(title: "Build On-Device Semantic Search") {
        Create a search index, fill it with vectors, query it by meaning, and
        persist it to disk â€” all on-device.

        You'll use ``HNSWIndex`` for fast approximate nearest-neighbor search,
        `NLEmbeddingProvider` from the `ProximaEmbeddings` library to turn text
        into vectors, and the built-in binary persistence to save and reload
        your index between launches.

        This tutorial assumes you've added both `ProximaKit` and
        `ProximaEmbeddings` to your target's dependencies â€” see
        <doc:GettingStarted> for installation.
    }

    @Section(title: "Create an index and add vectors") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Every search in ProximaKit runs against a vector index. In this
            section you create an ``HNSWIndex``, hand-craft a few small vectors
            so you can see exactly what the index stores, and run your first
            search.

            Real apps get their vectors from an embedding provider â€” that's the
            next section. Starting with hand-written 3-dimensional vectors keeps
            the mechanics visible.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Create an ``HNSWIndex``. You choose the vector dimension and the
                ``DistanceMetric`` up front; every vector you add must match that
                dimension. ``CosineDistance`` is the right default for text
                embeddings.

                Indices are Swift actors, so they're safe to share across tasks
                without any locking on your part.

                @Code(name: "FirstIndex.swift", file: "semantic-search-01-01.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Define some content to index. Each entry pairs a name with a
                ``Vector`` â€” just a list of `Float` components. Similar items
                point in similar directions: `apple` and `banana` are close,
                `bicycle` points elsewhere.

                @Code(name: "FirstIndex.swift", file: "semantic-search-01-02.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Add each vector with ``HNSWIndex/add(_:id:metadata:)``. The
                `UUID` identifies the vector in search results, and the optional
                metadata is JSON-encoded `Data` you get back with every match.

                `add` throws if a vector's dimension doesn't match the index,
                and it's an actor method â€” hence `try await`.

                @Code(name: "FirstIndex.swift", file: "semantic-search-01-03.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Search with ``VectorIndex/search(query:k:)``. It returns up to
                `k` ``SearchResult`` values sorted by distance â€” lower means
                more similar. Search never throws; note the `await` without
                `try`.

                Use ``SearchResult/decodeMetadata(as:)`` to recover the metadata
                you attached at insert time. With the query vector pointing in
                the "fruit" direction, the two fruit entries are the nearest
                neighbors.

                @Code(name: "FirstIndex.swift", file: "semantic-search-01-04.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Search by meaning with NLEmbeddingProvider") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Hand-written vectors show the mechanics, but the point of semantic
            search is that an embedding model writes them for you.
            `NLEmbeddingProvider` uses Apple's built-in NaturalLanguage
            framework â€” no model download, no API key.

            You'll embed a handful of notes, index them, and then find them with
            queries that share no words with the text they match.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Create the provider and size the index from it. The embedding
                dimension depends on the language model, so always use the
                provider's `dimension` property instead of hard-coding a number.

                `NLEmbeddingProvider` lives in the `ProximaEmbeddings` library,
                so this file needs both imports.

                @Code(name: "NoteSearch.swift", file: "semantic-search-02-01.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Embed and index some notes. `embed(_:)` converts each string
                into a ``Vector`` that captures its meaning; the note text rides
                along as metadata so search results can show it back to you.

                @Code(name: "NoteSearch.swift", file: "semantic-search-02-02.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                To search, embed the query with the same provider, then search
                the index with the resulting vector. The query and the indexed
                content must come from the same embedding model â€” vectors from
                different models aren't comparable.

                @Code(name: "NoteSearch.swift", file: "semantic-search-02-03.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Put it together. The query "a dog chasing a ball" returns the
                golden retriever note as its closest match â€” the two phrases
                share no meaningful words. That's the embedding model recognizing
                that dogs, retrievers, balls, and fetch belong together.

                @Code(name: "NoteSearch.swift", file: "semantic-search-02-04.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Persist and reload") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Embedding and indexing cost time at startup, so ProximaKit ships a
            versioned binary format that saves a full index â€” vectors, graph,
            and metadata â€” and loads it back directly, with no re-embedding and
            no graph rebuild.

            Saving compacts the index first, so tombstones from removed vectors
            never reach disk.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Save the index with ``HNSWIndex/save(to:)``. It's an actor
                method that throws on I/O failure, so call it with `try await`.

                @Code(name: "PersistAndReload.swift", file: "semantic-search-03-01.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Load it back with ``HNSWIndex/load(from:)``. It's a static
                factory â€” no index instance needed, and no `await` â€” that
                rebuilds a ready-to-search ``HNSWIndex`` from the file, throwing
                if the file is missing or corrupted.

                @Code(name: "PersistAndReload.swift", file: "semantic-search-03-02.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Round-trip your index: save it, reload it, and compare counts.
                The reloaded index contains every live vector, its metadata, and
                the full search graph â€” searches against it return the same
                results without re-adding anything.

                @Code(name: "PersistAndReload.swift", file: "semantic-search-03-03.swift")
            }
        }
    }
}
